<paragraph id="8BF5C554FF851869E0AEF8F8FE3DFEEA" blockId="1.[151,1436,1887,2033]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,152,658]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="43" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">
The Australian species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF85186AE1E9F8F8FDBFF8B8" box="[464,622,1887,1912]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF85186AE1E9F8F8FDBFF8B8" box="[464,622,1887,1912]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Horistothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are apparently fungal-hyphae feeders, living under the bark of dead trees. They are thus the ecological equivalent of species in the worldwide genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF85186AE465F820FAB8F861" authority="Hood" authorityName="Hood" box="[1116,1385,1927,1953]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplandrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF85186AE465F820FAF1F860" box="[1116,1312,1927,1952]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Hoplandrothrips</emphasis>
Hood
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF85186AE0AEF808FE2EF809" authority="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" box="[151,511,1967,1993]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF85186AE0AEF808FEF4F808" box="[151,293,1967,1992]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Hoplothrips</emphasis>
Amyot &amp; Serville
</taxonomicName>
although, curiously, no substantial colonies of either 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF85186AE44DF808FAD3F808" box="[1140,1282,1967,1992]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF85186AE44DF808FAD3F808" box="[1140,1282,1967,1992]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Hoplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF85186AE500F808FF0DF830" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF85186AE500F808FF0DF830" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Horistothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have been found in 
<collectingCountry id="F35D85C4FF85186AE21AF870FD43F831" box="[547,658,2007,2033]" name="Australia" pageId="1" pageNumber="42">Australia</collectingCountry>
, despite much searching of apparently suitable habitats. Moreover, only one undescribed species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E212FF3FFD18FF71" box="[555,713,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E212FF3FFD18FF71" box="[555,713,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Horistothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been collected. Presumably, the aridity of the climate, together with predation by Australia’s ubiquitous ant and arachnid species, inhibits the development on this continent of the large sub-cortical populations of hyphal-feeding phlaeothripines that can be so common in Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDBB8A5FF861869E0C2FEB7FE0EFEEA" author="Mound" box="[251,479,272,298]" pageId="2" pageNumber="60" refString="Mound, L. A., Morison, G. D., Pitkin, B. R. &amp; Palmer, J. M. (1976) Thysanoptera. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, 1 (2), 1 - 79." type="journal article" year="1976">
Mound et al., 
<number id="3D82D773FF861869E199FEB7FE0EFEEA" box="[416,479,272,298]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" value="1976.0">1976</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C35096DFFF861869E0FFFE9FFD8DFD52" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF5C554FF861869E0FFFE9FFD8DFD52" blockId="2.[151,1437,152,658]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">
Described as a monobasic genus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E263FE9FFD29FE91" box="[602,760,312,337]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E263FE9FFD29FE91" box="[602,760,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Horistothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has come to include 
<number id="3D82D773FF861869E3C0FE9FFBC7FE92" box="[1017,1046,312,338]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" value="10.0">10</number>
nominal species. Seven of these are from 
<collectingCountry id="F35D85C4FF861869E138FEC7FEA1FEBA" box="[257,368,352,378]" name="Australia" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Australia</collectingCountry>
, of which five are here placed into synonymy. The systematic relationships of the genus are not clear, but in contrast to members of such genera as 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E327FE2FFC7DFE61" box="[798,940,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E327FE2FFC7DFE61" box="[798,940,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Hoplothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E3DCFE2FFB78FE61" box="[997,1193,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Hoplandrothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E3DCFE2FFB78FE61" box="[997,1193,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Hoplandrothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E4C2FE2FFA43FE61" box="[1275,1426,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Phlaeothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E4C2FE2FFA43FE61" box="[1275,1426,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Phlaeothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
- lineage of fungus feeders (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDBB8A5FF861869E1F6FE17FD28FE0A" author="Mound" box="[463,761,432,458]" pageId="2" pageNumber="60" refString="Mound, L. A. &amp; Marullo, R. (1996) The Thrips of Central and South America: An Introduction. Memoirs on Entomology, International, 6, 1 - 488." type="journal article" year="1996">
Mound &amp; Marullo, 
<number id="3D82D773FF861869E283FE17FD28FE0A" box="[698,761,432,458]" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), the third antennal segment does not bear three sensoria. Instead, this segment has only a single sensorium, as in members of the leaf-feeding lineage of phlaeothripines related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E144FDA7FE39FDD9" box="[381,488,512,537]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Liothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E144FDA7FE39FDD9" box="[381,488,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Liothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The three non-Australian species listed in the genus have not been studied but, judging from their original descriptions, they seem unlikely to be closely related to the Australian species: 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E0AEFDF7FDFAFDAA" authority="Moulton" authorityName="Moulton" box="[151,555,592,618]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="claruspilus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E0AEFDF7FE6FFDA9" box="[151,446,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Horistothrips claruspilus</emphasis>
Moulton
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry id="F35D85C4FF861869E202FDF7FDBBFDAA" box="[571,618,592,618]" name="Fiji" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Fiji</collectingCountry>
); 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E247FDF7FBE2FDAA" authority="Moulton" authorityName="Moulton" box="[638,1075,592,618]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnafemora">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E247FDF7FC17FDA9" box="[638,966,592,617]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Horistothrips magnafemora</emphasis>
Moulton
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry id="F35D85C4FF861869E47AFDF7FBA3FDAA" box="[1091,1138,592,618]" name="Fiji" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Fiji</collectingCountry>
); 
<taxonomicName id="4C4ABED7FF861869E4BFFDF7FE22FD52" authority="Steinweden &amp; Moulton" authorityName="Steinweden &amp; Moulton" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Horistothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="palidispinosus">
<emphasis id="B93E1946FF861869E4BFFDF7FF0BFD51" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">Horistothrips palidispinosus</emphasis>
Steinweden &amp; Moulton
</taxonomicName>
(
<collectingCountry id="F35D85C4FF861869E23AFDDFFD9EFD52" box="[515,591,632,658]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="43">China</collectingCountry>
